Unless you have enough hashrate streams to meet the distribution of stake that all the Validators have

1. Validators publish pool information on the chain
2. Miners mine on the pool that each Validator publishes, with hashrate proportional to the stake of each Validator 
3. Validators use the hashrate to mine Bitcoin, either in pooled mining, by "solo" mining, or by reselling the hashrate to speculators
4. Validators score the hashrate that each miner contributes based on it's value at the time recieved. This allows us to score multiple algorithms of hashrate (e.g. BTC, KAS, LTC, XMR, etc.)
5. Validators submit weights to the chain based on the aggregate value of hashrate they received during the last period (1-2 epochs).
6. Miners get Alpha in exchange for the hashrate
7. Validators that want to keep their share of the hashrate, or get more, are incentivized to swap the mined BTC (and/or KAS, etc.) for Alpha.
